6)Automating Business process

Business process
	Business process is a series of steps performed by a group of stakeholders to archive a Goal.
 

  

 

Workflow

	We can create 500 workflows on a single object but only 50 workflows can be active.
o	In Immediate actions we can create up to 40 Actions(10 tasks, 10Email,10 Field update, 10 Outbound messages).
o	In Time based actions we can create up to 10 time Trigger for each trigger 40 Actions(10 tasks, 10Email,10 Field update, 10 Outbound messages).

	Workflows are automated process to send E-mail alerts, Assign task, Update fields on trigger criteria based requirements.
	In work flow we have 3 steps.
1)	Select Object: select object on which we have to create Workflow.
2)	Selection criteria: Define evaluation criteria and Rule criteria.
3)	Workflow Action: Create action to performed like Sending Email, update field, new out bound message and we add Time trigger to perform on specific time.

	Workflow rule is created on object level and we need to activate the Workflow rule.
	To create or change workflow rules, email alerts, tasks, field updates, and outbound messages: “Customize Application” Permission required for the user profile.

Navigation in classic 
	Setup->Build->Create-> Workflows and approvals.
Navigation in lightning
	Setup->Platform tools-> Process Automation->Workflow rules.
 

 

Evolution Criteria
 It will tell when I should check the rule. we have 3 option on evolution criteria.
	Created: Whenever new record created then it will check the rule.
	Created and every time it’s edited: whenever new record created or edited every time check the rule. We can’t create the Time base workflow actions with this option.
	Created and Any time it’s edited to subsequently meet criteria: Whenever new record created it will check the rule. 1st time modifying it will check the previous record if it meet the rule then don’t check. 2nd time modify previous record not meet the rule then check the rule.
	In below example rule is Amount > 5000.
o	When newly created rule was checked and meet the criteria
o	1st time modifying already newly created record meet the rule(7000> 5000) so don’t check the rule.
o	2nd time modifying already 1st time modified record meet the rule(9000>5000) so don’t check the rule.
o	3rd  time modifying already 2nd time modified record not meet the rule(2000 not Greater than the 5000) so check the rule.

 

Rule Criteria: These are 2 types. While creating rule we can use the Select objected data , parent object data, parent parent object data and current user login details.
1)	Criteria based: 
2)	Formula based:


Workflow Actions
Workflow actions are 2 types.
	Immediate actions 
o	Task
o	Email sent 
o	Field update 
o	Outbound message
	Time-based actions : 
o	Task
o	Email sent 
o	Field update 
o	Outbound message
Immediate Actions

1)	Task: Task is the Assigning the work to a user and notifying him when should be completed.
o	On standard objects we can create a task. While creating custom object if enable ‘Allow Activities’ Then only we can create task on Custom object. 
o	We check the assigned task at home page in My task section or if open the record, Activiti history we can see the assigned task.

 


o	We can assign task to User, Role or Owner.
o	If we assign the task to user then Task will be assigned to user. If we assign the task to Role(More than one user ) then Task will be assigned to owner of the record. If we assign the task to Role(Role have only one user) then Task will be assigned to Role user. 

 
o	If we assign the task to owner(User) then Task will be assigned to Owner. Suppose if the owner queue then task will be assigned to who user initiated the transaction.

o	In below example record created by owner(Faraz) and Divya Modified the transaction task will be assigned to Owner(Faraz). Second record created by the owner(HydTeam) and Diya modified the record criteria meet the workflow and task will be assigned to Diya because of owner is Queue and since she did transaction. 

 


2)	Send Email: Whenever criteria meet then sent an email notification. we have 4 type of email templates.
a)	Text: Normal Template
b)	HTML: We can apply styles like Bold, Italic and colors of the text using HTML functions.
c)	Custom (Without using classic Letter Head): Test
d)	Visual Force

Navigation in classic:
	Setup->Administer->Communication Templates->Email templates.
Navigation in Lightning:
	Setup->Administration->Email and choose lightning email template.

o	User can send 1000 emails for day and organization can send 20L emails per day.
o	Letter heading Lighting: To upload logo for letter head, go to classic environment and upload your logo in to Documents folder. Then use that logo in Lightning to crate enhanced letter head, Got o app launcher, enhanced letter head. Create letter head and use.

3)	Field update:
o	Using workflow, we can update the Current object fields or Master object(Having Master details relationship) fields only.
o	Example: If objects A(Master) and B(child) have master details relationship. if we create a Field update workflow on object ‘A’ then we can update only Object ‘A’ fields since it is master. If we create a Field update workflow on object ‘B’ then we can update Object ‘A’ and ‘B’ fields since it is master detail relationship.
 
o	Example: If objects A(Master) and B(child) have Lookup. if we create a Field update workflow on object ‘A’ then we can update only Object ‘A’ fields since it is master. If we create a Field update workflow on object ‘B’ then we can update ‘B’ fields since it is Lookup relationship.
o	If we crate more than one rule then it will evaluate first rules and perform actions. In below example on created record  rule1&2 are true perform action and rule 3 false don’t perform.

 

o	If both the actions(Rule1 And Rule2)  are trying to update the same field then order of  work flow rule created date updating result will  be shown. Suppose rule 2 created on 2-nov 2020 and rule1 created on 15 Nov-2020 the rule1 execute first and then rule2. Accordingly action as well .
o	If workflow rule1 and rule 2 have 2 actions then it will execute rule based creation date first and then action accordingly on date of creation.
o	All work rules first check the condition at record level before performing the action. In below example all rules are true at record level then execute rules and perform action date of creation.
o	At record level it will check all at once and the once true then it will execute below order. In Below example workflow Rule 3 will execute first(Because of it’s created on 17-Aug-2018) and then workflow rule action2 and action1. Then Workflow1 will execute and then work flow2 will execute.

 

o	 At record level if any rule fail then if we enable the ‘Re-evaluate workflow rules after field change’ then it will re-evaluate the all failed rules again. 
o	In Below Example we not enabled the re-evaluate option so on rule1 will execute.

 
o	In below example(Red Color) at record level Rule1 true and rule2 false but we enabled the revaluate on rule1 so first it will evaluate rule1 and update field. After field update it will re-evaluate failed rule2(Only failed rules, once rule true and executed then it will not execute again) now it true and update the field. For rule2 we did not enable the Re-evaluate option so it won’t check for any failed rules.
o	In below example (Green Color) at record level Rule1 true and rule2 false but we enabled the revaluate on rule1 so first it will evaluate rule1 and update field. After field update it will re-evaluate failed rule2 now it true and update the field. For rule2 also enabled the Re-evaluate option so it checks for is there any failed exist if yes it will re-evaluate those else nothing will happen (Again rule1 will not execute since it is already executed).


 

o	While creating field update action we can enable the ‘Re-evaluate workflow rules after field change’ Option. 

 


4)	Outbound Message
o	If we want to send the some information from SFDC to some third party system through Web services after evaluation criteria matched will go with the Outbound message.
o	Outbound Messages—Send a secure, configurable API message (in XML format) to a designated listener.
o	Example: Trigger an outbound API message to an external HR system to initiate the reimbursement process for an approved expense report.
o	While creating Outbound message we need to provide the third-party web service URL.

Time-based Actions

	Action will execute the on time interval given. For Single work flow we can create up to 10 time triggers and for each time trigger we can create 40 actions. We create time trigger calculation on date field like Rule Trigger date, Record created date, record last modified date and date fields in the object.
	While activating the Time based work flow rule we need to provide the Default workflow user(While executing the time based workflow rule who is user) and Email Approval Sender( Enabling email approval response lets users reply to email approval requests by typing APPROVE or REJECT in the first line and adding comments in the second line.)
	To check Time based rule trigger added or not got to below navigation or check the Debug Logs.
Classic:
	Setup-> Monitor-> Time-based workflow then provide the details in Filter conditions.
Lightning:
	Setup-> platform Tools->environments->Monitor-> Time-based workflow then provide the details in filter conditions.

Debug logs: first add the to debug log then create a record now we can be able to see the order of execution in debug logs.

Use Case1: In Below example rule(City= Hyd) is true and Time trigger added to execute on 5-July-2019 But on 30-Jun-2019 some one modified the record changed the city to ‘Bang’. Now on execution day action will perform or Not.

Sol: On record creation date rule is true then trigger added but if some modified and rule is false because of the Modification then the trigger will be removed from the queue. Trigger it self not there so no action will be performed.  To see this enable Debug log for the user and perform below example.


 
Use Case2: If the date is postponed then exist trigger execution date will update accordingly. In Above example if the date in record modify to 2-Jul-2019 then execution date of trigger will be updated to 12-July-2019.
Use Case3: If the date is preponed then exist trigger will be deleted and created new trigger with the dates accordingly. In Above example if the date in record modify to 10-Jun-2019 then New trigger will be added and execution date is 20-Jun-2019.
Use case4: If the calculated execution date if less than today then how when the trigger will executed. Salesforce starts to process the field update within an hour after you create the record.
	
		



 Process Builder

	Process Builder: It is also same as of workflow only but in workflow we can able to update the fields only in current object or Master object whereas in process builder we can be able update fields in both master and child object as well. 
	In below example if we want archive below conditions in workflow we need to create 3 work flow rules but in in process builder we can do all with one process builder.
 

	In process builder when condition meet we can create a record on any object.
	using workflow we can’t post message in Chatter but in Process builder we can post message in chatter.
	In process builder we can call Apex classes but not in workflow.
	We can submit the record for approval in process builder not in Workflow.
	Process builder can be called once record created/Modified or Other process builder can call process builder.

Navigation in classic 
	Setup->Build->Create-> Workflows and approvals->Process Builders.
Navigation in lightning
	Setup->Platform tools-> Process Automation->Process Builder.
	One process builder activated we can’t modify it either we can create a new process builder or we can clone it to a new version.
	In process builder also we have ‘Immediate action’ and ‘scheduled action’.

 

In process builder Task is nothing but we need to select ‘create a new record’ action and then create a record in Task object.
 

Approval Process

	Approval Process:
 Trail head: Building a discount approval process

 

 
 
 
	Approval process are 2 types
o	Jump Start wizard: Single step and simple process
o	Standard setup wizard: Single step complex process or multistep complex process.

Navigation in classic
	Setup->Build->Create-> Workflows and approvals then Approval process.
Navigation in lightning
	Setup->Platform tools-> Process Automation->Approval process.
	We need to activate the Approval process to perform.
	If you want send the record for Approval, we need to check the submitter user have access on that record or not.
Jump Start Wizard

Steps In Jump start wizard: Select Object and select type Approval process as Jump start wizard.
 

1)	Name of the Approval process
2)	Entry Criteria: Filter condition 
3)	Specify Approver field and record editability properties: Specify the approver name (Who need to approve the record like manger. In this step if ) and who can edit the record only Admin or Admin along with current assigned approver.

o	In Below Example record owner is Sam. If we are not enabled the ‘Use Approver field of account owner’ then Ram is submitting the record for Approval process then it will be assigned  Ram’s manger(Submitter manger).
o	In Below Example record owner is Sam. If we are enabled the ‘Use Approver field of account owner’ then Ram is submitting the record for Approval process then it will be assigned  to Sam  manger(Account owner  manger).

 


 



4)	Select Email template: Select email template that send to Approver
5)	Select Fields to display on Approval page layout.
6)	Specify initial Submitters. Who will submit the record for approval process like User, owner, Public groups, Role and Role&Sub. In this step we can enable the allow submitters to Recall approval requests option.

Standard Step Wizard

Steps In Standard step : Select Object and select type Approval process as Standard step start wizard.     
 
1)	 Name of the Approval process
2)	Entry Criteria: If entry criteria is meet then we can able submit the record for Approval otherwise we can’t submit for approval. 
3)	Specify Approver field and record editability properties: Specify the approver name (Who need to approve the record like manger. In this step if ) and who can edit the record only Admin or Admin along with current assigned approver.
o	In Below Example record owner is Sam. If we are not enabled the ‘Use Approver field of account owner’ then Ram is submitting the record for Approval process then it will be assigned  Ram’s manger(Submitter manger).
o	In Below Example record owner is Sam. If we are enabled the ‘Use Approver field of account owner’ then Ram is submitting the record for Approval process then it will be assigned  to Sam  manger(Account owner  manger).

 


 

4)	Select Email template: Select email template that send to Approver
5)	Select Fields to display on Approval page layout.
6)	Specify initial Submitters. Who will submit the record for approval process like User, owner, Public groups, Role and Role&Sub. In this step we can enable the allow submitters to Recall approval requests option.

Once Approval process created we can configure following actions.
 
	Initial Submission actions: Once record is submitted for Approval then it will be locked automatically. That movement when we submit the record for approval Record will locked apart from that if we want to perform any actions Email, Outbound, task And field update then we can configure in this section.
	Approval Steps: 
o	select the who can approve the request or we can select the approver at the time Submitting as well in section.

 

o	In Approval we can create number of steps and it execute in sequence manner like Step1, 2 and so on. Also we can specify all records should go through this step or we can specify the criteria. 
 
Step1: Step sequence
 
                Step2: Specify the criteria.
 
Step3: Select Assign Approver. We can specify the approver Automally or manually in this step.
 
o	The approve can be able to the see all the record waiting for his approval in home page ‘Items to Approve’ Section.
 
o	If we submit the record for more than one user then it is called as ‘Parallel Approval process’. These are 2 types
a)	First Response: Approve or reject based on the First response coming from the either user1 Or user2.
b)	Unanimous: Required to get approval from All the approvers then only record will be approved. If anyone user reject, then record will get rejected.
Example: Claim for International trip. After submitting the expense report need to get the approve from Workday manger, Finance team and finally Accounting team. If all are approved, then Expense report will approve. If in one rejected it will get rejected.
o	In this approval steps section, after creating the approval step we can create actions to the Approval or Rejection like Task, Email alert, Outbound message and Field update. 

 

 
	Final Approval Action: In this Section By default record will be in lock for editing. If we want, we can choose Unlock record for editing. Along with this we can perform actions like task, Email Alert, Field update and Outbound message.
 


	Final rejection Actions: In this Section By default record will be in unlock for editing. If we want, we can choose lock record for editing. Along with this we can perform actions like task, Email Alert, Field update and Outbound message.
 

	Recall Actions: In this Section By default record will be in unlock for editing. If we recall the record, then we can be able to edit the record by default. Along with this we can perform actions like task, Email Alert, Field update and Outbound message.
 

	If we send a record to a queue for approval if any one of user in queue can approve/reject. 
	Suppose few records sent for User ‘A’ approval now due to some reason we need to Reassign all request from User ‘A’ to User ‘B’ then we will go with ‘Mass transfer Approval request’.
 
Delegated Approver: Record assigned for the User Approval, if we configure delegated approver in User setting then on behalf of User, delegated approver can also take the decision like Approve/Reject. While creating approval process if we enable the option ‘The approvers delegated may also approve the request’ then delegated approver also can approve the request.
Example. On User ‘A’ we have configured delegated approver as User ‘B’. Now if submitted record for Approval from user ‘A’ then either user ‘A’ or User ‘B’ can approve/reject the record.
Navigation:
Administer->Manage users-> Users-> Click edit on the particular user.
Chatter Post: While creating custom object we need to enable the allow chatter. With chatter also we can approve the record. While creating the approval process in step4 we can select the chatter template.
Navigation in classic:
Administer->Build->Customize -> Chatter -> Chatter settings -> edit then enable the chatter settings. 
Navigation in Lightning:
Administration->Platform tolls->Feature settings->Chatter-> Chatter settings -> edit then enable the chatter settings. 
o	Also here we have option ‘Approval posts’ if we enable this then we can approve the record from chatter itself.
o	After enabling chatter go to the feed tracking and select the Object and select the fields which want to display in chatter message.
o	For chatter templates we can create in post template option in Workflows and approval section and this post template we can use in Chatter.
Email Notification: Through email also we can be able approve the request. While creating the approval process in step4 we can select the email template. Once approver receives an email if he replied like Approved/yes then request will approve or replied like reject/No then request will be rejected.
Navigation in classic:
	Setup->Administer->Communication Templates->Email templates.
Navigation in Lightning:
	Setup->Administration->Email and choose lightning email template.
Approval in Chatter: 
	To enable Approval requests in Chatter:
o	From Setup, enter Chatter Settings in the Quick Find box, and then click Chatter Settings.
o	Click Edit and In the Approval Posts section, select Allow Approvals.

Lightning Flow

	Lightning Flow: these 2 types i.e screen flow and Auto launched flow.
Trail head: flow basics and Lightning flow.
 

 


	Lightning Flow—the product(The name of the tool) that encompasses building, managing, and running flows and processes.
	Flow Builder—a point-and-click tool for building flows.
	Flow Interview: it is nothing but once flow stated it will be callas the Flow Interview. If we want to see this to the flow debug the step is the Flow interview.

 

	Flow—the part of Lightning Flow that automates a business process by collecting data and doing something in your Salesforce org or an external system.

	Flows are two types 
o	Screen flow: it will mainly user interface involved.
o	Auto lunched flow: No user interface. Work in backend. Auto lunched flow need some input so basically we will give it from Process builder(It is one example).
 
 
 

	In Flow builder divided into 3 blocks
1)	Elements
2)	Connectors
3)	Resources
1)	Element: Each element is a step in the flow that instructs the flow on what to do. Those instructions vary based on which kind of element it is. We like to think of flow elements in terms of three different buckets: screens, logic, and actions.
o	Screens: Display data to your users or build a form to collect information from them with Screen elements.
The Runtime Experiences: these setting are there in Process automation setting
There’s one more important consideration for screen components: which flow runtime experience they’re supported in.
Flows have two different runtime experiences: Lightning runtime and Classic runtime. Like its name suggests, Lightning runtime looks and feels like Lightning Experience, while Classic runtime looks and feels like Visualforce.

All screen components are supported in Lightning runtime, but not all screen components are supported in Classic runtime. Here are three indicators that a component requires Lightning runtime.
•	The component icon is a lightning bolt.
•	No preview is available for the component. 
•	A warning that a screen component requires Lightning runtime appears when the flow is saved. 
Make Your Flows Look Like Lightning
	Salesforce offers two runtime experiences that determine the look and feel when someone runs a flow. To make your flows blend in with Lightning Experience, make sure that Lightning runtime is enabled in your org.
	From Setup, enter Automation in the Quick Find box, and then select Process Automation Settings.
	Verify that Enable Lightning runtime for flows is selected and Save your changes.

o	Logic: Once you collect the data you need, what do you want to do with it? With logic elements, evaluate that data and manipulate it according to your business requirements. Create branches, update data, loop over sets of data, or pause until a specified time. Logic operates only in the flow. If you use logic elements to evaluate or manipulate information in your flow, the resulting data can’t be accessed after the flow finishes. Use an action to store that data somewhere outside of the flow.

o	Actions: Actions instruct the flow to do something outside of itself, such as in the Salesforce database or in an external system. Flows can look up, create, update, and delete Salesforce records. They can also create Chatter posts, submit records for approval, and send emails.                                                                                                                                                                                  

Action Types
Without creating or configuring anything else in Salesforce, you can use these actions.

	Post to Chatter.
	Send Email.
	Submit For Approval.
	Activate or Deactivate a Permission Set.
	Global or object-specific actions provided by Salesforce.
You can also include actions you create with clicks.

	Other flows in your org are available in the Subflow element.
	Custom global or object-specific actions are available in the Action element.
You can also include actions that require code. And you can install custom actions from AppExchange or a third-party library.
	To do something in the Salesforce database, build or install an Apex action.
	To do something in the browser, build or install a local action.

 

2)	Connectors: Connectors define the path that the flow takes as it runs. They tell the flow which element to execute next. It like a Arrow.
3)	Resources: Resources are placeholders that you reference throughout your flow. For example, look up an account’s ID, store that ID in a variable, and later reference that ID to update the account.
Type of resources:
o	Variable
o	Constant
o	Formula
o	text 
o	choice
o	Record choice set
o	Pick list choice set
o	Stage. 

Data Type	Use to store...
Text	IDs, descriptions, and other text or long text data.
Record	Field values from a record, such as an opportunity. When this data type is selected, you create a record variable.
Number	A numeric value.
Currency	A currency values.
Boolean	A yes/no value, such as whether a checkbox was selected.
Date	A date value
Date/Time	A date and time value.
Picklist	A picklist value
Multi-Select Picklist	Picklist values, separated by semicolons.
Apex-Defined	Field values from an Apex class. When this data type is selected, you create an Apex-defined variable.

	How many values should the variable store?
By default, variables store one value that’s compatible with the selected data type. If the data type is Number, the variable stores one numeric value. If the data type is Record, the variable stores field values for one record.
But what if you need to store multiple values in one variable, such as multiple email addresses? When you create a variable, you can enable it to do just that with the ‘Allow multiple values’ checkbox. When that option is selected, you need to create a collection variable.
	Should the value be available from outside the flow? 
Each variable in your flow gets its value from somewhere. Some variables get their values from inside the flow, such as when the user enters something in a screen component or the flow looks up field values from a record.
Other variables get their values from outside of the flow—namely, from whatever started the flow. For example, if your process builder started the flow of  an Account record page, you can pass the account’s ID into the flow by using the flow’s input variables. An input variable is a variable that has the Available for input checkbox selected.
If whatever starts the flow should be able to set the value of a variable, make sure the variable is available for input. When in doubt, go ahead and make your variable available for input.

When you configure your variable, you see another checkbox: Available for output. When selected, you’ve created an output variable, which means the value is accessible to something outside the flow.

	Flows need to search in Setup to create lightning flow.
	In Flow we can use run button to do sanity check whether your flow working properly or not also we can do the debug using Debug button.
	We need to activate the flow to available for users.
	In flow we have a Versioning. Once flow activated if we want to do any changes on that if we want to do changes then deactivate and created a new version by cloning it. 
	If it is a screen based lighting flow then create Lighting app builder to add screen flows to the app. Auto lunched flows can be invoked by the process builder.
	Testing Options in Flow Builder
o	Run: runs the most recent saved version of the flow that you have open.
o	Debug: does everything that Run does, but with some superpowers thrown in. It lets you enter values for the flow’s input variables and display debug details while running the flow. That way, you can verify how the flow processes data.
	Flow Interview
Each time a flow runs, a flow interview starts. A flow interview is an instance of a flow. Based on the data provided for that interview, either by input variables or input components on a screen, each interview can take a different path through the flow and result in different actions being performed.
	Permissions required: 
o	In the profile ’Manage flows’ This option enabled users only can create and activate the flows.
o	If the user doesn’t have the ‘Manage Flows’ permission, then user want to Run the flow then he required any one of the below permission.
	The Run Flows user permission
 
	The Flow User field enabled on their user detail page
 

	If we want to check the each flow access, Click on the flow edit action in action bar then If Override default behavior and restrict access to enabled profiles or permission sets is selected for an individual flow, access to that flow is given to users by profile or permission set.  
If we enable the override option then only particular profile users can be run the Flow.
 
	Flow Actions
A flow action is a custom action that renders a flow, and as such it’s perfectly suited to these kinds of use cases. Once you create a flow action and add it to a page layout, it appears in the associated record's page-level action menu in Lightning Experience where users can find it to launch the flow.

Navigation:
o	From Setup, click the Object Manager tab. Click Contact, then click Buttons, Links, and Actions.
o	Click New Action and select type as flow. 

 

